<P>
SUNDAY NIGHT, NETWORKS GO TO THE MOVIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE WEINSTEIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The networks will battle it out Sunday night with three new TV movies about 
murder, mystery and marriage. 
</P>
<P>
With no baseball scheduled until the World Series begins next Tuesday, CBS 
(2)(8) will air "Murder Times Seven" Sunday at 9 p.m. Richard Crenna reprises 
his role as New York detective Frank Janek, who investigates a mass murder only 
to be hampered by one of the victims' ex-wife. 
</P>
<P>
NBC (4)(36)(39) counters with "A Quiet Little Neighborhood, a Perfect Little 
Murder," a goofy little suspense comedy starring Teri Garr and Robert Urich. 
</P>
<P>
ABC (7)(3)(10)(42), meanwhile, offers "In Defense of a Married Man." In this 
courtroom drama, a man (Michael Ontkean) accused of murdering his mistress is 
defended by his wife (Judith Light). 
</P>
<P>
At the same hour Sunday, Channel 9 offers "The Next Disaster -- Are You 
Prepared?" This one-hour special, hosted by Robert Conrad, is designed to help 
viewers survive the next earthquake, flood, tornado or fire by presenting 
footage of past tragedies like Hurricane Hugo and last year's Bay Area 
earthquake, with advice on how to handle such emergencies. STEVE WEINSTEIN 
</P>
</TEXT>
