<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON CAMPUS: PIERCE COLLEGE; 
</P>
<P>
CHILD-CARE FUNDING IS SLASHED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAN DOW, Compiled from reports of campus correspondents and Times staff 
writers. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cuts in child-care funding at Pierce College and the other eight Los Angeles 
Community College District campuses are limiting the schools' ability to serve 
student parents, college officials said. 
</P>
<P>
Kathy Ryder, Child Development Center director at the Woodland Hills school, 
said the cost of this year's program at Pierce, if run at its present capacity, 
will be $312,835. However, she said she has only about $290,000. 
</P>
<P>
Pierce's center has a capacity of 60 children. Because of state regulations 
regarding teacher-child ratios, six full-time teachers are needed to operate 
the center at that capacity from 8 a.m. to 3 p.m., Ryder said. 
</P>
<P>
However, the center currently has only four full-time teachers and one 
part-time teacher. In addition, one of the full-time teachers, Norma Silverman, 
plans to take maternity leave in the next couple of weeks and the Pierce 
administration has thus far refused to hire a substitute. 
</P>
<P>
"Unless we close a class, we will be illegal in some way," Ryder said. 
</P>
<P>
Speakers from throughout the community college district attended a district 
Board of Trustees meeting Oct. 3 at Pierce to voice their concerns about budget 
cuts for the child-care centers. 
</P>
<P>
Michael Simone of East Los Angeles College said the district allotment of $2.3 
million is about $572,000 less than last year's expenditure. "The colleges have 
been left holding the bag," he said. "This bag is empty." 
</P>
<P>
"I would not have the opportunity to be a full-time student if it were not for 
child care," said Barbara Kime, a 28-year-old single parent attending Pierce. 
</P>
<P>
The speakers asked the board to adopt a set of guidelines that would, among 
other things, assure that child-care centers with two classrooms have four 
teachers and those with four classrooms have six. 
</P>
<P>
Pierce, along with four other district schools, has a four-classroom center. 
The other four schools have two-classroom centers. DAN DOW 
</P>
</TEXT>
