<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON CAMPUS: COLLEGE OF THE CANYONS; 
</P>
<P>
PRIVATE FIRM TO RUN BOOKSTORE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JACI D. ANTRAM, Compiled from reports of campus correspondents and Times 
staff writers. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Santa Clarita Community College District Board of Trustees this week 
approved a three-year contract that will allow a private firm to operate and 
manage the College of the Canyons bookstore. 
</P>
<P>
Trustees voted Wednesday night to award Follette College Stores a contract to 
take over the campus store Nov. 1. 
</P>
<P>
The contract guarantees the district $75,000 a year or 7.2% of sales between $1 
million and $1.5 million and 7.6% of sales above $1.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
Under the new management, students will receive reduced book prices. More used 
books, updated technology, additional staff, extended operating hours, internal 
improvements and special promotions also are included in the new contract. 
</P>
<P>
A major concern of college officials was the continued employment of its own 
full-time employees at the bookstore. The company agreed to place the COC 
employees under contract and to offer them full benefits. 
</P>
<P>
"They will pay the entire cost of our benefits," said Dianne Van Hook, district 
superintendent-president. "That is an added bonus for us." 
</P>
<P>
A committee of faculty members and students investigated reports of high prices 
at the college-run store for the last year. 
</P>
<P>
Trustees selected Follette College Stores over three competitors. 
</P>
<P>
Lower book prices will not be immediately evident because of inflation, said 
Trustee Linda Cubbage. JACI D. ANTRAM 
</P>
</TEXT>
