</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The South African government postponed a key reform in retaliation for a blast 
of criticism from Nelson Mandela's African National Congress. Justice Minister 
Hendrik J. Coetseesaid that, following ANC accusations that Pretoria was trying 
to undermine black-white reconciliation, he would delay announcing guidelines 
for the release of political prisoners and the return of exiles. The two issues 
are among the ANC's conditions for entering formal negotiations with the white 
government on ending apartheid and enfranchising the black majority. 
